    "## ðŸ›‘ PILLAR 1: Standard Deviation & The Math of Jitter
",
    "
",
    "### The Thinking
",
    "Malware needs to check in with its Command & Control (C2) server. If it does this every exactly 60 seconds, it's easy to catch. To hide, malware adds **Jitter** (e.g., 60 seconds +/- 10 seconds). 
",
    "
",
    "### The Math
",
    "We use **Standard Deviation (Ïƒ)** to measure how much our "beacons" vary from the average.
",
    "- **Low Ïƒ:** Highly automated, consistent (Strong Indicator of C2).
",
    "- **High Ïƒ:** Inconsistent, bursty (Typical Human Behavior).
",
    "
",
    "**Task:** Let's simulate three types of traffic and see how the math reveals the attacker."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np
",
    "import pandas as pd
",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
",
    "import seaborn as sns
",
    "
",
    "# 1. Perfect Beacon (No Jitter)
",
    "perfect = np.array([60, 60, 60, 60, 60])
",
    "
",
    "# 2. Jittered Malware (Small variance)
",
    "jittered = np.array([58, 62, 59, 61, 60])
",
    "
",
    "# 3. Human Traffic (High variance)
",
    "human = np.array([12, 450, 30, 1200, 5])
",
    "
",
    "print(f"Perfect StdDev: {np.std(perfect):.2f}")
",
    "print(f"Jittered StdDev: {np.std(jittered):.2f}")
",
    "print(f"Human StdDev: {np.std(human):.2f}")"
   ]
