    "## ðŸ›‘ PILLAR 4: Index of Coincidence (IC) & Crypto Identification
",
    "
",
    "### The Thinking
",
    "Before cracking a code, you must know what kind of code it is. A Caesar cipher keeps the English letter distribution, just "rotated." A Vigenere cipher "flattens" the distribution to look like random noise.
",
    "
",
    "### The Math
",
    "**Index of Coincidence (IC)** calculates the probability that two randomly selected letters from a text are the same. 
",
    "- **IC â‰ˆ 0.066:** English Plaintext or Caesar Cipher (Monoalphabetic).
",
    "- **IC â‰ˆ 0.038:** Random noise or Vigenere Cipher (Polyalphabetic).
",
    "
",
    "**Task:** Observe how the IC changes when we move from English to a more complex cipher."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def calculate_ic(text):
",
    "    text = ''.join(filter(str.isalpha, text.upper()))
",
    "    N = len(text)
",
    "    freqs = [text.count(c) for c in 'ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ']
",
    "    ic = sum(f * (f - 1) for f in freqs) / (N * (N - 1))
",
    "    return ic
",
    "
",
    "msg = "THE ENEMY IS APPROACHING FROM THE WEST AT DAWN"
",
    "random_noise = "ZKD LWNMX LV DSURDFKLQJ IURP WKH ZHVW DW GDZQ"
",
    "
",
    "print(f"Plaintext IC: {calculate_ic(msg):.4f}")
",
    "print(f"Ciphertext IC: {calculate_ic(random_noise):.4f}")"
   ]
